				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ayers" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1856789); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1856789&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252364" alt="Ayers" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1856789)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ayers" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1856789); return false;" >Ayers</a></span> <span class="odate time_1556878849 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">03 May 2019 10:20</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4237176">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Because its anomalous properties sound like a Dungeons and Dragons campaign where the DM is pre-emptively trying to outwit a party of power-gaming munchkins.</p>
<p>To establish terror, you need verisimilitude. And to establish verisimilitude, you need to make your anomaly feel authentic — not designed.</p>
<p>The less anomalous it is, the more real it starts to feel.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>These three quotes explain something I've had to spend paragraphs on in the past &#8212; I think it applies to a lot more than just writing horror. I've called it &quot;overpowered&quot;, &quot;over-bloated&quot;, and &quot;overly-complex&quot; in the past, but those terms never felt right or properly captured my intent.</p>
<p>Thanks for putting this out Hippo. I know a lot of people (myself included) don't have a clue when it comes to cultivating terror. I hope to spook some people soon.</p>
