					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3938622); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3938622&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252364" alt="The Great Hippo" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3938622)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3938622); return false;" >The Great Hippo</a></span> <span class="odate time_1556961587 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">04 May 2019 09:19</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4238234">
									

<p>I didn't get around to commenting on this till just now (busy with RL), but I wanted to point this out:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I think it applies to a lot more than just writing horror.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I agree, and this is one of the things that led to this essay taking so long to write. I kept struggling over my desire to make it <em>just</em> about how to make anomalies &quot;authentic&quot; (rather than &quot;designed&quot;), and how this can establish verisimilitude in any genre (not just terror).</p>
<p>There's still a lot of ground I wish I had covered. I wrote a throwaway line about not bothering to address certain 'problems' (&quot;why can't the Foundation just&#8230;?&quot; &#8212; Answer: &quot;For reasons not elaborated in the article.&quot;), but it deserves more elaboration. There's also more to be said about making your anomaly 'out of reach', and 'so subtle it's almost non-anomalous'.</p>
<p>There's also an entire other essay to be written regarding the creation of terror not through verisimilitude, but by <em>proxy</em> &#8212; establishing characters and immersive set-pieces, then allowing us to dread what horrors await them (see <strong><a href="/scp-3001">SCP-3001</a></strong>, <strong><a href="/shaggydredlocks-proposal">S. D. Locke's proposal</a></strong>, and most of <strong><a href="/metaphysician">Metaphysician</a></strong>'s work).</p>

							</div>

								
