															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/augmentedspartan" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1775542); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1775542&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252364" alt="augmentedspartan" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1775542)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/augmentedspartan" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1775542); return false;" >augmentedspartan</a></span> <span class="odate time_1559233935 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 May 2019 16:32</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4266432">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Verisimilitude — how &quot;authentic&quot; a thing feels; Deviation — how this thing deviates from the familiar; and Insinuation — how, despite not knowing its purpose, we still know its purpose is terrifying.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I love this bit. It's also a good indicator as to why the entire essay is good - it's concise but easy to understand. A problem when analyzing horror is that sometimes it's difficult to explain aspects without using emotive or subjective language because you can't exactly describe horror with technical language, but I think this overcomes that issue by the very well done comparison between the two similar SCPs.</p>
<p>My only issue is this part:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>What's more terrifying: That all the shadows around you are filled with monsters?<br />
Or that there was never anything there at all?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>While the latter might be more interesting in fiction, the former is always scarier in real life.</p>

							</div>

								
					
