					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3938622); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3938622&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252364" alt="The Great Hippo" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3938622)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3938622); return false;" >The Great Hippo</a></span> <span class="odate time_1559262496 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">31 May 2019 00:28</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4266738">
									

<p>Thanks! And yeah one of the things I really strive for with these essays (and with advice in general) is to provide <em>concrete</em> advice with demonstrative examples (rather than abstract advice that resembles more 'words of wisdom' than actual principles you can use to achieve very straightforward results).</p>
<p>Re: that final dig, I agree it's scarier in real life to imagine monsters in the shadows, but I think &#8212; in fiction &#8212; dread and terror are strange creatures, and what is dreadful in reality isn't always dreadful in fiction (and vice versa).</p>
<p>I'll concede, however, that I <em>may</em> have written that last bit just because I liked the way it sounded. &gt;_&gt;</p>

