					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4535508">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kungfusloth" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6142323); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6142323&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252364" alt="kungfusloth" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6142323)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kungfusloth" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6142323); return false;" >kungfusloth</a></span> <span class="odate time_1583555382 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Mar 2020 04:29</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4535508">
									

<p>I'm no expert, but I do have an interest in cosmic horror in the iconic Lovecraftian style (such as Call of Cthulu), minus the racism. The way you described terror sounds a lot like his formula of maintaining a hold in reality while showing the reader how fragile the reality is. I think your last bit about the monsters never being there sums up his quote nicely: &quot; The oldest and strongest emotion of mankind is fear, and the oldest and strongest kind of fear is fear of the unknown.&quot; Because if we could see the monsters, they would become the 'known'; our new reality.</p>
<p>I'm not accusing you of stealing from Lovecraft. After all, his style is so ubiquitous that most good horror stories use it. I just wanted to express my gratitude for this article. A big concern I had when deciding to join the site is the seemingly contradictory notion of being able to contain the unknown. I wasn't sure if a cosmic entity could be portrayed as scary or horrifying when depicted as an engineering project. I now see that a good horror writer can show terror even in a technical manual, without having to resort to addendums.</p>
<p>This has me excited to try it out!</p>

							</div>

								
					
